.TH "MIDD" "1" "June 2026" "Version 1.0.5" "Midd User Manual"
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
midd - extracts precise, bounded intervals of lines from a stream or
file
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]midd\f[R] [\f[B]-i\f[R] \f[I]input\f[R]] [\f[B]-o\f[R]
\f[I]output\f[R]] [\f[B]-r\f[R] \f[I]range\f[R]] [\f[B]-l\f[R]]
[\f[B]-1\f[R]] [\f[B]-q\f[R]] [\f[B]-p\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]midd\f[R] extracts precise, bounded intervals of lines from a
stream or file.
Unlike traditional tools that load entire datasets into memory or
continue reading files long after the target range has passed,
\f[B]midd\f[R] utilizes a fail-fast validation layer and terminates
execution the exact moment its upper-bound constraint is satisfied.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]-i\f[R] \f[I]input\f[R]
Path to the input file.
Default is STDIN.
.TP
\f[B]-o\f[R] \f[I]output\f[R]
Path to the output file.
Default is STDOUT.
.TP
\f[B]-r\f[R] \f[I]range\f[R]
The target line range formatted strictly as
\f[I]start\f[R]:\f[I]end\f[R].
Default is \f[V]$:$\f[R] (full file).
.TP
\f[B]-l\f[R]
Enables visual line numbering prefixes in the output.
Default is disabled.
.TP
\f[B]-1\f[R]
Shifts range parsing and line numbering to 1-indexed mode.
Default is 0-indexed.
.TP
\f[B]-q\f[R]
Quiet mode.
Suppresses informational slice boundary markers.
Default is disabled.
.TP
\f[B]-p\f[R]
Printable-only mode.
Strips non-printable characters.
Default is disabled.
.SH RANGE SYNTAX
.PP
The \f[B]-r\f[R] flag accepts flexible bounding parameters using an
integer or the \f[V]$\f[R] symbol (representing End-of-File):
\[bu] .RS 2
.TP
\f[B]10:50\f[R]
Extracts from line 10 to line 50.
.RE
\[bu] .RS 2
.TP
\f[B]100:$\f[R] or \f[B]100:\f[R]
Extracts from line 100 to the end of the file.
.RE
\[bu] .RS 2
.TP
\f[B]$:25\f[R] or \f[B]:25\f[R]
Extracts from the beginning of the file up to line 25.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
\f[B]Extracting a Specific Slice (0-Indexed, with Line Numbers)\f[R]
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
midd -i raw_data.txt -r 10:15 -l
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Output:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
[ SLICE START: 10 ]
10 | Eleventh line of the file
11 | Twelfth line of the file
12 | Thirteenth line of the file
13 | Fourteenth line of the file
14 | Fifteenth line of the file
15 | Sixteenth line of the file
[ SLICE END: 15 ]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
\f[B]Matching Text Editor Coordinates (1-Indexed, Quiet Output)\f[R]
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
midd -i source_code.cpp -r 10:12 -l -1 -q
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Output:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
10 | // Tenth line matching your IDE
11 | int main() {
12 |     setup_variables();
\f[R]
.fi
.SH CORE ARCHITECTURE & VALIDATION
.PP
\f[B]Fail-Fast Range Policy\f[R] To prevent wasteful compute cycles or
script cascading failures, \f[B]midd\f[R] validates the range integrity
before processing.
If a range is provided where the start parameter is greater than the end
parameter (e.g., \f[V]-r 50:20\f[R]), the tool will immediately print an
explicit error to STDERR and exit with status code 1.
.PP
\f[B]Data Stream Sanitization (-p)\f[R] When running in printable-only
modes, the utility filters incoming byte streams to sanitize binary
noise while preserving structural text alignment.
Standard layout control characters (\f[V]\[rs]n\f[R], \f[V]\[rs]r\f[R],
\f[V]\[rs]t\f[R]) are explicitly allowed through the filter, while raw
control characters and non-printable binary junk are dropped.
